         /quote<BR>No, your missing his point. The only real difference between a DoT and a Regen spell is a DoT has a negative HP modifier while a Regen has a positive one. They are essentially just the opposite sides of a coin. <BR>/end quote</P><P>Nope, I didn't miss his point. Dot's are not regen debuffs. Regen debuffs stop regen. Calling our dot's is like calling a DD spell an instant temporary regen debuff. After all you did counteract the regened health the mob would have recieved for that round (and more that it would have gained in future rounds). </P><P>Dot's are slow working DD's. They are our primary DAMAGE source. I don't cast a dot to stop some mob from regening. I cast it to Dmg it. I cast a disease based spell to stop it from regening, but that is only for the DEBUFF <u>ASPECT</u>of it.</P><P>I was trying to correct him. I was trying to make him understand the difference between a regen debuff and a dot. Again, a regen debuff STOPS regeneration. A dot does it's dmg over time. Big difference and a very bad choice in labels. Calling a dot a regen debuff is like calling a DD a rune debuff. When is the last time you used a mana intensive DD spell to debuff a mob's rune or skin spell? Sure it works, but would you really call it a debuff? </P><P>I also take it that no one found any fault with my numbers. In which case I have to wonder how multiple necros stacking their dots on a raid could ever be considered overpowering. </P><P>Yes, all dot's would have to stack to be fair IMO. I have no problem with that and hope they get it as well.</P><P><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=264137" target="_blank" target="_blank">Charbonez Soulmark</a><BR>Duzzil Ro<a href="#top"><img src="icon_go_up.gif" height="15" width="15" border="0" align="right" alt="Go to Top of Page"></a></font></td>
